Google Symptoms Dataset¶

Explore potentially useful symptoms using linear regression¶

Jingjing Tang 2020-11-19

  • Use county level data only
  • Calculate time series correlations across locations (ignore nan, filter out counties with <20% days available)
    • Since the raw data are pre-scaled using region specific maximum values at a certain time point picked by Google, they are not comparable between regions.
    • Huge variance in geographical coverage and temporal coverage among symptoms
  • Using linear regression to see the coefficients of different symptoms
    • NAs are filled with 0s
    • Note that due the time series property, actually the rows are not random samples that can we directly used for a traditional prediction
    • We only want to see the variable important here, not trying to get good prediction results
  • Negative correlations and negative coefficients got from linear model can be explained by the lag in time. Thus, we need to consider the symptoms with large absolute time series correlation first. Except for our current selection Anosmia and Ageusia, Dysgeusia is definitely another choice. Besides, respiratory related symptoms such as Laryngitis and Tachypnea are also good candidates with large negative correlations. The difference in the sign of the correlation also raises another interesting question: how the lag in time differs among symptoms.

def get_geo_id(region_code):
    """
    There are region code in the format of "US-state" and "US-state-fips". In
    county level report, we only consider rows with fips info provided.
    """
    splits = region_code.split("-")
    if len(splits) == 3:
        return splits[2]
    return np.nan

dfs = {}
# For state level data
df = pd.read_csv(base_url.format(sub_url="/", state=""), parse_dates = ["date"])
df["geo_id"] = df["open_covid_region_code"].apply(lambda x: x.split("-")[1].lower())
dfs["state"] = df

# For county level data
dfs["county"] = pd.DataFrame(columns = dfs["state"].columns)
for state in list(STATE_TO_ABBREV.keys()):
    sub_url = "/subregions/" + "%20".join(state.split("_")) + "/"
    df = pd.read_csv(base_url.format(sub_url=sub_url, state=state+"_"), parse_dates = ["date"])
    df["geo_id"] = df["open_covid_region_code"].apply(get_geo_id)
    dfs["county"] = dfs["county"].append(df)

# Add District of Columbia County
try:
    df_dc_county = dfs["state"][dfs["state"]["geo_id"]=="dc"].drop("geo_id", axis = 1)
    df_dc_county.loc[:, "geo_id"] = DC_FIPS
    dfs["county"] = dfs["county"].append(df_dc_county)
except KeyError:
    pass

dfs["state"].to_csv("state_google_symptoms.csv", index=False)
dfs["county"].to_csv("county_google_symptoms.csv", index=False)

Correlation Across Location¶

Note that since the data is not comparable between regions (since the values are scaled based on region specific maximum values at a certain time point), we will only consider time-series correlation.

In [469]:
# Read GS data
gs_df = pd.read_csv("county_google_symptoms.csv", parse_dates=["date"]).drop(
                      ['open_covid_region_code', 'country_region_code', 'country_region',
                       'sub_region_1', 'sub_region_1_code', 'sub_region_2',
                       'sub_region_2_code'],
                    axis = 1)
gs_df = gs_df[~gs_df["geo_id"].isnull()]
gs_df["geo_id"] = [str(int(x)).zfill(5) for x in gs_df["geo_id"]]

# Read case data from API 
start_date = datetime(2020, 2, 20)
end_date = datetime(2020, 11, 9)
api_df = covidcast.signal("usa-facts", "confirmed_7dav_incidence_prop", 
                        start_date, end_date, "county").rename(
                        {"geo_value":"geo_id", "value": "cases", "time_value": "date"},
                        axis = 1)[["geo_id", "date", "cases"]]
df = gs_df.merge(api_df, on=["date", "geo_id"])

For manually Selected 25 COVID-related Symptoms¶

It takes too long to run the correlation for all of the symptoms. Will start from a list of potentially COVID-related symptoms only (I took a rough look at all search terms and filtered them according to the relevant symptoms listed by CDC) and then go back to brute-force.

Linear Regression¶

In [419]:
all_predictors = selected_predictors.copy()
X = df.loc[:, all_predictors].fillna(0)
y = df.loc[:, "cases"].fillna(0)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.10, random_state=3)  
    
# Train the model
reg = LinearRegression().fit(X_train.values , y_train)
pred = reg.predict( X_test.values )
mse = mean_squared_error(pred, y_test)
In [422]:
sorted_idx = np.argsort(reg.coef_)
pos = np.arange(25) + .5

plt.figure(figsize = (10, 10))
plt.barh(pos, reg.coef_[sorted_idx][-25:], align='center')
plt.yticks(pos, np.array(all_predictors)[sorted_idx][-25:])
plt.xlabel('Coef')
plt.title('Coefficients in Linear Regression Model \n(raw value, using selected symptoms only)')

For All of the 422 symptoms¶

In [246]:
i = 0
corr_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=["county", "symptom", "correlation", "pvalue"])
for idx in range(1, len(df.columns)-2):
    symptom = df.columns[idx].split(":")[1]
    subdf = df[[df.columns[idx], "cases", "geo_id"]].dropna()
    mask_df = subdf.groupby("geo_id").count()
    # Filter out counties with more than 80% days unavailable
    geo_list = set(mask_df[mask_df[df.columns[idx]] >= n_day*0.2].index.values)
    subdf = subdf[subdf["geo_id"].isin(set(geo_list))]
    for county in set(geo_list):
        local_df = subdf[subdf["geo_id"] == county]
        corr, p = spearmanr(list(local_df.values[:, 0]), list(local_df.values[:, 1]), nan_policy="omit")
        corr_df.loc[i] = [county, symptom, corr, p]
        i += 1
    print("Finished calculation for %s"%symptom)
corr_df.to_csv("GS_spearman_corr.csv", index=False)

Here is a table to show the mean, median, standard deviation of spearman correlation between the search volumes and confirmed_7dav_incidence_prop from USA-Facts. They are calculated across regions where values are available for more than 20% of days (264 days in total as stated above). The table is sorted by the mean of correlation.

In [334]:
corr_df = pd.read_csv("GS_spearman_corr.csv")
sorted_mean = corr_df.groupby("symptom").mean().reset_index()[["symptom", "correlation"]]
sorted_std = corr_df.groupby("symptom").std().reset_index()[["symptom", "correlation"]]
sorted_median = corr_df.groupby("symptom").median().reset_index()[["symptom", "correlation"]]
summary_df = sorted_mean.merge(sorted_median, on="symptom", suffixes=["_mean", "_median"]
                       ).merge(sorted_std, on="symptom"
                       ).sort_values("correlation_mean", ascending=False
                       ).rename({"correlation": "correlation_std"}, axis=1)

                 df[df["geo_id"] == str(county).zfill(5)]["symptom:%s"%target_symptoms[i]])

plt.tight_layout()

The negative correlation is caused by lag in time between the confirmation of cases and the appearance of the symptosm. When we calculate the spearman correlation, we don't add suitable time lag for different regions. There is an apparent increasing trand in mid March for confirmed cases. However, people usually search for symptoms such as Laryngitis several days early than cases being confirmed.

So, symptoms with large negative correlation are also important ones to look at. This might raise another interesting problm:

The appearance of different symptoms has different effects on people's reaction.

Anosmia and Ageusia stand out probably because they are special enough. People with relatively more common symptoms like fever and cough will not rush to get tested for COVID.

Linear Regression¶

Train on data for different state (ignore this part, not very useful)¶

In [489]:
coef_raw_rank_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=(list(all_predictors) + ['mse', 'state']))
coef_abs_rank_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=(list(all_predictors) + ['mse', 'state']))
coef_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=(list(all_predictors) + ['mse', 'state']))
i = 0
best_predictor_set = [all_predictors]
for state in df["state_id"].unique():
    state_df = df[df["state_id"] == state]
    X = state_df.loc[:, all_predictors].fillna(0)
    y = state_df.loc[:, "cases"].fillna(0)
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.10, random_state=3)  
    
    # Train the model
    reg = LinearRegression().fit(X_train[best_predictor_set[0]].values , y_train)
    pred = reg.predict( X_test[best_predictor_set[0]].values )
    mse = mean_squared_error(pred, y_test)
    coef_raw_rank_df.loc[i] = list(rankdata(reg.coef_)) + [mse, state]
    coef_abs_rank_df.loc[i] = list(rankdata([abs(x) for x in reg.coef_])) + [mse, state]
    coef_df.loc[i] = list(reg.coef_) + [mse, state]
    i += 1

Due the hugh variance in geographical coverage, we should be careful when considering the plot above. We get the absolute values of coefficients from the linear regression model and calculate the rank. Here in the violin plot, we draw the distribution of rank across different states. Compared with the model using data for all of the counties to train, we achieve much smaller mse (e.g. ~3-7) for certain states. For the rest, the mse can range from <10 to > 1000.
